the United States confident that
the military rulers

35:48.880 --> 35:53.752 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
are going to let her and her
party essentially take over?

35:53.752 --> 35:56.721 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
TOM MALINOWSKI: Well, we take
absolutely nothing for granted.
This has been a tough struggle

35:56.721 --> 36:00.291 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
in Burma for many
years, as I mentioned.

36:00.291 --> 36:04.896 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But the military has promised,
including the commander in chief
just in the last few days,

36:04.896 --> 36:09.334 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
that they will respect the
results. And I think, having
gone this far, I think it will

36:09.334 --> 36:13.605 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
be quite hard for them
to turn back now.

36:13.605 --> 36:17.108 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: What are the
chief challenges going forward,
whoever is victorious in the

36:17.108 --> 36:17.909 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
Parliament?

36:17.909 --> 36:20.712 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
TOM MALINOWSKI: Well,
there are several.

36:20.712 --> 36:27.352 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
First, the country is still
operating under a non-democratic
constitution, which gives

36:27.352 --> 36:32.290 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the military, as I mentioned, a
quarter of the seats in
Parliament, which gives them,

36:32.290 --> 36:36.394 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
actually, a veto power over
changes in the constitution, the
right to appoint the interior

36:36.394 --> 36:38.663 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
ministers.

36:38.663 --> 36:44.235 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The police in Burma still
answers to the military and not
to the civilian government. The
constitution,

36:44.235 --> 36:48.339 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Aung San Suu Kyi and her party
have said, will need to change.
And that's something

36:48.339 --> 36:52.377 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
that we have -- we, the United
States, have called for us as
well.

36:52.377 --> 36:57.449 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And then there's perhaps the
deepest and most difficult
problem, and that is that, well,

36:57.449 --> 36:59.717 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
one of the flaws of this
election was that hundreds of
thousands of people, the
Rohingya

36:59.717 --> 37:00.085 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
Muslims...

37:00.085 --> 37:01.920 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Right.

37:01.920 --> 37:05.924 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
TOM MALINOWSKI: ... who had
previously been able to vote in
Burma, had lived there for

37:05.924 --> 37:12.831 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
generations, were
disenfranchised, were denied the
vote, because of a really
virulent, racist

37:12.831 --> 37:19.137 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
campaign that was staged we
think in part to try to deny the
opposition a victory in

37:19.137 --> 37:21.406 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
this election.

37:21.406 --> 37:27.045 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
But that racism, that
intolerance that was created for
the purpose of this election is

37:27.045 --> 37:30.482 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
